Consider the following C declaration:
struct {
    short x[5];
    union {
        float y;
        long z;
    } u;
} t;
Assume that the objects of the type short, float and long occupy 2 bytes, 4 bytes and 8 bytes, respectively. The memory requirement for variable t, ignoring alignment considerations, is:
A. 22 bytes
B. 14 bytes
C. 18 bytes
D. 10 bytes

Consider the program below in a hypothetical programming language which allows global variables and a choice of static or dynamic scoping.

int i;
program main() {
    i = 10;
    call f();
}
procedure f() {
    int i = 20;
    call g();
}
procedure g() {
    print i;
}

Let x be the value printed under static scoping and y be the value printed under dynamic scoping. Then, x and y are:
A. x = 10, y = 20
B. x = 20, y = 10
C. x = 10, y = 10
D. x = 20, y = 20
